AGI - The President of the United States, Joe Biden>, said that he will convene on Sunday the leaders of the G7 to coordinate a "united diplomatic response" to the "fronted" <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-04-13/iran-lancia-decine-droni-israele-attack-netanyahu-idf-ultime-noti The White House tenant said that the American forces helped the Jewish state to break down "almost all" bullets thrown against its territory and assured that the American military were not put in the sight. According to U.S. administration sources cited by the NBC, Biden fears that the Israeli prime minister responds too fretly to the unprecedented offensive of the Islamic Republic and in the phone call of the past hours, add other well informed, would ask Tel Aviv not to react.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
"Iran - and its delegates from Yemen, Syria and Iraq - launched an unprecedented air strike against military facilities in Israel. They condemn these attacks in the strongest possible terms," Biden said. The President of the United States has explained that he has ordered U.S. military aircraft and ballistic missile defense destroyers to head to the Middle East in recent days, when the likely Iranian threat to the U.S. regional ally has become clear.
&nbsp;
"Thanks to these deployments and the extraordinary ability of our military, we have helped Israel to break down almost all drones and missiles incoming," Biden continued, explaining that he spoke with Netanyahu to "reaffirm America's ferreous commitment" for Israel's security. "I told him that Israel has demonstrated a remarkable ability to defend and defeat even unprecedented attacks, sending a clear message to its enemies: they cannot effectively threaten Israel's security."
<h2> The doubts of Washington</h2>
Biden, according to Nbc, would have been worried that Netanyahu is trying to drag the United States deeper into a wider conflict. The White House believes that the Israelis are not looking for a direct confrontation with Iran, in the light of the resources used in the war in Gaza, but it is not certain. U.S. officials expressed in private frustration for Tel Aviv's decision to strike the Iranian consular building in Syria on 1 April, stating that Israeli leaders did not reflect on the time and implications of the attack, including the possible consequences on negotiations for the release of hostages held by Hamas, still explains the Nbc. "I don't think they had a strategy," said a senior administration officer, "The Israelis don't always make the best strategic decisions."
&nbsp;
In the days prior to Iran's retaliation against Israel, the U.S. intelligence warned that Iranian leaders felt the need to respond to an operation seen as an attack on their territory to avoid internal problems. The official described Israel's approach to military operations as "frenetic". A defence officer echoed this feeling, saying that the Israelis have proven to be much better in operations than in planning. "We've been out of sight with their very short-term planning in recent months, so in this sense the attack in Damascus is not so surprising," he concluded.

