&nbsp;
Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan> decided to respond to the allegations raised on social media: in the last few weeks the messages in which Turkey was accused of doing business with the Jewish State, forgetting the Palestinian population. The dissemination of this information contributed to the collapse of the Erdogan party in the administrative elections on 31 March. Before October 7 and the beginning of the Turkey and Israel conflict had normalized diplomatic relations after a decade of controversy and accusations. The long history of tensions between the two countries, which has always been caused by Israeli policies towards the Palestinians, has not affected trade. This time things have gone differently and since last October some chains of Israeli supermarkets have blocked the import of Turkish products and in general, according to official data, trade between the two countries had already dropped by 33% before sanctions.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The new measures are intended to have a further impact on the economies of the two countries. Turkish exports to the Jewish State of 2023 amounted to $5.4 billion, 2.1% of the total exports of Ankara (according to the data of the Ministry of Economy). It is also the fruit of a free trade treaty signed in 1996 and the exemption from taxation on certain products entered into force in 2000. These agreements allowed Turkey to triple the volume of trade between the two countries between 2009 and 2023>, making Turkey the fifth exporter to Israel and the Jewish State the tenth importer for Ankara. Turkish exports to Israel are based on steel, mechanical, chemical products, electronic appliances, textiles, cement, glass, ceramics, paper and forestry products. 60% of the trade volume between the two countries is Turkish exports, the remaining 33% from Israeli exports.
&nbsp;
It is the steel export sector which is intended to suffer the heaviest consequences of sanctions: every year Turkey exports to Israel 726 thousand tons of steel, 20% of the total exported by Turkish companies that produce this material. Israel will have to deal with the ban on the sale of cement decided by the Turkish Government. 30% of the cement imported from the Jewish State comes from Turkey every year and the price of houses and apartments is intended to engulf. Precisely the blockade to the sale of concrete, bricks and building material, at a time when houses and infrastructures, especially at the Lebanese border, need repairs, is destined to have political consequences. On the contrary, 11% of the plastic imported from Turkey comes from Israel and also here Ankara will have to look for alternatives.
&nbsp;
The heaviest consequence is, however, the end of the prospect of a collaboration for a pipeline that leads to Europe the Israeli gas through Turkey: to this project the two countries were actively working before October 7. The sanctions decided by Ankara are likely to have an impact on the Palestinian population. The ports of Haifa and Ashdod are in fact the landing points, Israelis, for the products destined to the West Bank >. The volume of trade interchange between Turkey and the West Bank has grown in recent years until the billion dollars on an annual basis. The sale of iron, steel, wood, vegetable oil, tobacco, food makes Turkey the second supplier on the Palestinian market after Israel.&nbsp;

